  "prompt": "How is gender determined genetically?",
  "response": "Gender determination is primarily dictated by the chromosomes an individual inherits from their parents. In humans, these chromosomes include 23 pairs, with one pair being the sex chromosomes. The sex chromosomes are labeled X and Y.\n\n1. **Chromosomal Basis**:\n   - Females typically have two X chromosomes (XX).\n   - Males typically have one X and one Y chromosome (XY).\n\n2. **Role of the Y Chromosome**:\n   - The presence of the Y chromosome determines male sex. Specifically, the SRY (Sex-determining Region Y) gene located on the Y chromosome initiates the development of male characteristics. SRY triggers the formation of testes, which produce male hormones like testosterone, leading to the development of male physical traits.\n\n3. **Absence of the Y Chromosome**:\n   - In the absence of a Y chromosome (as in XX individuals), the default developmental pathway proceeds toward female characteristics. In typical females, the ovaries develop, and estrogen becomes the predominant hormone, influencing female physical traits.\n\n4. **Intersex Variations**:\n   - It's important to note that not all individuals fit neatly into the XX/XY framework. Some individuals may have atypical combinations of sex chromosomes (e.g., XXY, XYY) or variations in sexual development, leading to intersex conditions.\n\nIn summary, gender is determined genetically by the combination of sex chromosomes inherited from the parents, with the presence of a Y chromosome typically leading to male development and its absence resulting in female development.",
